ACL.summary: A container for Access List Control commands

ACL CAT.summary: List the ACL categories or the commands inside a category
ACL CAT.complexity: O(1) since the categories and commands are a fixed set.

ACL DELUSER.summary: Remove the specified ACL users and the associated rules
ACL DELUSER.complexity: O(1) amortized time considering the typical user.

ACL DRYRUN.summary: Returns whether the user can execute the given command without executing the command.

ACL GENPASS.summary: Generate a pseudorandom secure password to use for ACL users

ACL GETUSER.summary: Get the rules for a specific ACL user
ACL GETUSER.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of password, command and pattern rules that the user has.
history: Added selectors and changed the format of key and channel patterns from a list to their rule representation.

ACL HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

ACL LIST.summary: List the current ACL rules in ACL config file format
ACL LIST.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

ACL LOAD.summary: Reload the ACLs from the configured ACL file
ACL LOAD.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

ACL LOG.summary: List latest events denied because of ACLs in place
ACL LOG.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of entries shown.

ACL SAVE.summary: Save the current ACL rules in the configured ACL file
ACL SAVE.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

ACL SETUSER.summary: Modify or create the rules for a specific ACL user
ACL SETUSER.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of rules provided.
history: Added selectors and key based permissions.

ACL USERS.summary: List the username of all the configured ACL rules
ACL USERS.complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

ACL WHOAMI.summary: Return the name of the user associated to the current connection

APPEND.summary: Append a value to a key
APPEND.complexity: O(1). The amortized time complexity is O(1) assuming the appended value is small and the already present value is of any size, since the dynamic string library used by Redis will double the free space available on every reallocation.

ASKING.summary: Sent by cluster clients after an -ASK redirect

AUTH.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of passwords defined for the user

BGSAVE.summary: Asynchronously save the dataset to disk

BITCOUNT.summary: Count set bits in a string

BITFIELD.summary: Perform arbitrary bitfield integer operations on strings

key_specs.notes: This command allows both access and modification of the key

BITFIELD_RO.summary: Perform arbitrary bitfield integer operations on strings. Read-only variant of BITFIELD

BITPOS.summary: Find first bit set or clear in a string

BLMOVE.summary: Pop an element from a list, push it to another list and return it; or block until one is available

BLMPOP.summary: Pop elements from a list, or block until one is available
BLMPOP.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of provided keys and M is the number of elements returned.

BLPOP.summary: Remove and get the first element in a list, or block until one is available
BLPOP.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of provided keys.
history: `timeout` is interpreted as a double instead of an integer.

BRPOP.summary: Remove and get the last element in a list, or block until one is available
BRPOP.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of provided keys.
history: `timeout` is interpreted as a double instead of an integer.

BRPOPLPUSH.summary: Pop an element from a list, push it to another list and return it; or block until one is available
history: `timeout` is interpreted as a double instead of an integer.

BZMPOP.summary: Remove and return members with scores in a sorted set or block until one is available
BZMPOP.complexity: O(K) + O(N*log(M)) where K is the number of provided keys, N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

BZPOPMAX.summary: Remove and return the member with the highest score from one or more sorted sets, or block until one is available
BZPOPMAX.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.
history: `timeout` is interpreted as a double instead of an integer.

BZPOPMIN.summary: Remove and return the member with the lowest score from one or more sorted sets, or block until one is available
BZPOPMIN.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.
history: `timeout` is interpreted as a double instead of an integer.

CLIENT.summary: A container for client connection commands

CLIENT CACHING.summary: Instruct the server about tracking or not keys in the next request

CLIENT GETREDIR.summary: Get tracking notifications redirection client ID if any

CLIENT HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

CLIENT ID.summary: Returns the client ID for the current connection

CLIENT INFO.summary: Returns information about the current client connection.

CLIENT KILL.summary: Kill the connection of a client
CLIENT KILL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections
history: Replaced `slave` `TYPE` with `replica`. `slave` still supported for backward compatibility.

CLIENT LIST.summary: Get the list of client connections
CLIENT LIST.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections
history: Added `laddr` field and the optional `ID` filter.

CLIENT NO-EVICT.summary: Set client eviction mode for the current connection

CLIENT PAUSE.summary: Stop processing commands from clients for some time
history: `CLIENT PAUSE WRITE` mode added along with the `mode` option.

CLIENT REPLY.summary: Instruct the server whether to reply to commands

CLIENT TRACKING.summary: Enable or disable server assisted client side caching support
CLIENT TRACKING.complexity: O(1). Some options may introduce additional complexity.

CLIENT TRACKINGINFO.summary: Return information about server assisted client side caching for the current connection

CLIENT UNBLOCK.summary: Unblock a client blocked in a blocking command from a different connection
CLIENT UNBLOCK.complexity: O(log N) where N is the number of client connections

CLIENT UNPAUSE.summary: Resume processing of clients that were paused
CLIENT UNPAUSE.complexity: O(N) Where N is the number of paused clients

CLUSTER ADDSLOTS.summary: Assign new hash slots to receiving node
CLUSTER ADDSLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

CLUSTER ADDSLOTSRANGE.summary: Assign new hash slots to receiving node
CLUSTER ADDSLOTSRANGE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of the slots between the start slot and end slot arguments.

CLUSTER COUNT-FAILURE-REPORTS.summary: Return the number of failure reports active for a given node
CLUSTER COUNT-FAILURE-REPORTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of failure reports

CLUSTER COUNTKEYSINSLOT.summary: Return the number of local keys in the specified hash slot

CLUSTER DELSLOTS.summary: Set hash slots as unbound in receiving node
CLUSTER DELSLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

CLUSTER DELSLOTSRANGE.summary: Set hash slots as unbound in receiving node
CLUSTER DELSLOTSRANGE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of the slots between the start slot and end slot arguments.

CLUSTER FAILOVER.summary: Forces a replica to perform a manual failover of its master.

CLUSTER FLUSHSLOTS.summary: Delete a node's own slots information

CLUSTER FORGET.summary: Remove a node from the nodes table

CLUSTER GETKEYSINSLOT.summary: Return local key names in the specified hash slot
CLUSTER GETKEYSINSLOT.complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of requested keys

CLUSTER HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

CLUSTER INFO.summary: Provides info about Redis Cluster node state

CLUSTER KEYSLOT.summary: Returns the hash slot of the specified key
CLUSTER KEYSLOT.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of bytes in the key

CLUSTER LINKS.summary: Returns a list of all TCP links to and from peer nodes in cluster
CLUSTER LINKS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

CLUSTER MEET.summary: Force a node cluster to handshake with another node

CLUSTER NODES.summary: Get Cluster config for the node
CLUSTER NODES.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

CLUSTER REPLICAS.summary: List replica nodes of the specified master node

CLUSTER REPLICATE.summary: Reconfigure a node as a replica of the specified master node

CLUSTER RESET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of known nodes. The command may execute a FLUSHALL as a side effect.

CLUSTER SAVECONFIG.summary: Forces the node to save cluster state on disk

CLUSTER SET-CONFIG-EPOCH.summary: Set the configuration epoch in a new node

CLUSTER SETSLOT.summary: Bind a hash slot to a specific node

CLUSTER SHARDS.summary: Get array of cluster slots to node mappings
CLUSTER SHARDS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of cluster nodes

CLUSTER SLAVES.summary: List replica nodes of the specified master node

CLUSTER SLOTS.summary: Get array of Cluster slot to node mappings
CLUSTER SLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

COMMAND.summary: Get array of Redis command details
COMMAND.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Redis commands

COMMAND COUNT.summary: Get total number of Redis commands

COMMAND DOCS.summary: Get array of specific Redis command documentation
COMMAND DOCS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands to look up

COMMAND GETKEYS.summary: Extract keys given a full Redis command
COMMAND GETKEYS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of arguments to the command

COMMAND GETKEYSANDFLAGS.summary: Extract keys and access flags given a full Redis command
COMMAND GETKEYSANDFLAGS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of arguments to the command

COMMAND HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

COMMAND INFO.summary: Get array of specific Redis command details, or all when no argument is given.
COMMAND INFO.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands to look up
history: Allowed to be called with no argument to get info on all commands.

COMMAND LIST.summary: Get an array of Redis command names
COMMAND LIST.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Redis commands

CONFIG.summary: A container for server configuration commands

CONFIG GET.summary: Get the values of configuration parameters
CONFIG GET.complexity: O(N) when N is the number of configuration parameters provided
history: Added the ability to pass multiple pattern parameters in one call

CONFIG HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

CONFIG RESETSTAT.summary: Reset the stats returned by INFO

CONFIG REWRITE.summary: Rewrite the configuration file with the in memory configuration

CONFIG SET.summary: Set configuration parameters to the given values
CONFIG SET.complexity: O(N) when N is the number of configuration parameters provided
history: Added the ability to set multiple parameters in one call.

COPY.complexity: O(N) worst case for collections, where N is the number of nested items. O(1) for string values.

DBSIZE.summary: Return the number of keys in the selected database

DECR.summary: Decrement the integer value of a key by one

DECRBY.summary: Decrement the integer value of a key by the given number

DEL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys that will be removed. When a key to remove holds a value other than a string, the individual complexity for this key is O(M) where M is the number of elements in the list, set, sorted set or hash. Removing a single key that holds a string value is O(1).

DISCARD.summary: Discard all commands issued after MULTI
DISCARD.complexity: O(N), when N is the number of queued commands

DUMP.summary: Return a serialized version of the value stored at the specified key.
DUMP.complexity: O(1) to access the key and additional O(N*M) to serialize it, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1).

EVAL.summary: Execute a Lua script server side
EVAL.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

key_specs.notes: We cannot tell how the keys will be used so we assume the worst, RW and UPDATE

EVALSHA.summary: Execute a Lua script server side
EVALSHA.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

EVALSHA_RO.summary: Execute a read-only Lua script server side
EVALSHA_RO.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

EVAL_RO.summary: Execute a read-only Lua script server side
EVAL_RO.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

key_specs.notes: We cannot tell how the keys will be used so we assume the worst, RO and ACCESS

EXEC.summary: Execute all commands issued after MULTI
EXEC.complexity: Depends on commands in the transaction

EXISTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to check.

EXPIRE.summary: Set a key's time to live in seconds

EXPIREAT.summary: Set the expiration for a key as a UNIX timestamp

EXPIRETIME.summary: Get the expiration Unix timestamp for a key

FAILOVER.summary: Start a coordinated failover between this server and one of its replicas.

FCALL.complexity: Depends on the function that is executed.

key_specs.notes: We cannot tell how the keys will be used so we assume the worst, RW and UPDATE

FCALL_RO.complexity: Depends on the function that is executed.

key_specs.notes: We cannot tell how the keys will be used so we assume the worst, RO and ACCESS

FLUSHALL.summary: Remove all keys from all databases
FLUSHALL.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of keys in all databases

FLUSHDB.summary: Remove all keys from the current database
FLUSHDB.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys in the selected database

FUNCTION DUMP.summary: Dump all functions into a serialized binary payload
FUNCTION DUMP.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of functions

FUNCTION FLUSH.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of functions deleted

FUNCTION HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

FUNCTION KILL.summary: Kill the function currently in execution.

FUNCTION LIST.summary: List information about all the functions
FUNCTION LIST.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of functions

FUNCTION LOAD.summary: Create a function with the given arguments (name, code, description)

FUNCTION RESTORE.summary: Restore all the functions on the given payload
FUNCTION RESTORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of functions on the payload

FUNCTION STATS.summary: Return information about the function currently running (name, description, duration)

GEOADD.summary: Add one or more geospatial items in the geospatial index represented using a sorted set
GEOADD.complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

GEODIST.summary: Returns the distance between two members of a geospatial index

GEOHASH.summary: Returns members of a geospatial index as standard geohash strings
GEOHASH.complexity: O(log(N)) for each member requested, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

GEOPOS.summary: Returns longitude and latitude of members of a geospatial index
GEOPOS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members requested.

GEORADIUS.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members matching a given maximum distance from a point
GEORADIUS.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GEORADIUSBYMEMBER.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members matching a given maximum distance from a member
GEORADIUSBYMEMBER.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GEORADIUSBYMEMBER_RO.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GEORADIUS_RO.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GEOSEARCH.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members inside an area of a box or a circle.
GEOSEARCH.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the grid-aligned bounding box area around the shape provided as the filter and M is the number of items inside the shape

GEOSEARCHSTORE.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members inside an area of a box or a circle, and store the result in another key.
GEOSEARCHSTORE.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the grid-aligned bounding box area around the shape provided as the filter and M is the number of items inside the shape

GET.summary: Get the value of a key

GETBIT.summary: Returns the bit value at offset in the string value stored at key

GETDEL.summary: Get the value of a key and delete the key

GETEX.summary: Get the value of a key and optionally set its expiration

key_specs.notes: RW and UPDATE because it changes the TTL

GETRANGE.summary: Get a substring of the string stored at a key
GETRANGE.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the returned string. The complexity is ultimately determined by the returned length, but because creating a substring from an existing string is very cheap, it can be considered O(1) for small strings.

GETSET.summary: Set the string value of a key and return its old value

HDEL.summary: Delete one or more hash fields
HDEL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields to be removed.

history: `protover` made optional; when called without arguments the command reports the current connection's context.

HEXISTS.summary: Determine if a hash field exists

HGET.summary: Get the value of a hash field

HGETALL.summary: Get all the fields and values in a hash
HGETALL.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

HINCRBY.summary: Increment the integer value of a hash field by the given number

HINCRBYFLOAT.summary: Increment the float value of a hash field by the given amount

HKEYS.summary: Get all the fields in a hash
HKEYS.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

HLEN.summary: Get the number of fields in a hash

HMGET.summary: Get the values of all the given hash fields
HMGET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being requested.

HMSET.summary: Set multiple hash fields to multiple values
HMSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being set.

HRANDFIELD.summary: Get one or multiple random fields from a hash
HRANDFIELD.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields returned

HSCAN.summary: Incrementally iterate hash fields and associated values
HSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..

HSET.summary: Set the string value of a hash field
HSET.complexity: O(1) for each field/value pair added, so O(N) to add N field/value pairs when the command is called with multiple field/value pairs.

HSETNX.summary: Set the value of a hash field, only if the field does not exist

HSTRLEN.summary: Get the length of the value of a hash field

HVALS.summary: Get all the values in a hash
HVALS.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

INCR.summary: Increment the integer value of a key by one

INCRBY.summary: Increment the integer value of a key by the given amount

INCRBYFLOAT.summary: Increment the float value of a key by the given amount

INFO.summary: Get information and statistics about the server
history: Added support for taking multiple section arguments.

KEYS.summary: Find all keys matching the given pattern
KEYS.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of keys in the database, under the assumption that the key names in the database and the given pattern have limited length.

LASTSAVE.summary: Get the UNIX time stamp of the last successful save to disk

LATENCY.summary: A container for latency diagnostics commands

LATENCY DOCTOR.summary: Return a human readable latency analysis report.

LATENCY GRAPH.summary: Return a latency graph for the event.

LATENCY HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands.

LATENCY HISTOGRAM.summary: Return the cumulative distribution of latencies of a subset of commands or all.
LATENCY HISTOGRAM.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands with latency information being retrieved.

LATENCY HISTORY.summary: Return timestamp-latency samples for the event.

LATENCY LATEST.summary: Return the latest latency samples for all events.

LATENCY RESET.summary: Reset latency data for one or more events.

LCS.complexity: O(N*M) where N and M are the lengths of s1 and s2, respectively

LINDEX.summary: Get an element from a list by its index
LINDEX.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse to get to the element at index. This makes asking for the first or the last element of the list O(1).

LINSERT.summary: Insert an element before or after another element in a list
LINSERT.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse before seeing the value pivot. This means that inserting somewhere on the left end on the list (head) can be considered O(1) and inserting somewhere on the right end (tail) is O(N).

LLEN.summary: Get the length of a list

LMOVE.summary: Pop an element from a list, push it to another list and return it

LMPOP.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of provided keys and M is the number of elements returned.

LOLWUT.summary: Display some computer art and the Redis version

LPOP.summary: Remove and get the first elements in a list
LPOP.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements returned

LPOS.summary: Return the index of matching elements on a list
LPOS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements in the list, for the average case. When searching for elements near the head or the tail of the list, or when the MAXLEN option is provided, the command may run in constant time.

LPUSH.summary: Prepend one or multiple elements to a list
LPUSH.complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

LPUSHX.summary: Prepend an element to a list, only if the list exists
LPUSHX.complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

LRANGE.summary: Get a range of elements from a list
LRANGE.complexity: O(S+N) where S is the distance of start offset from HEAD for small lists, from nearest end (HEAD or TAIL) for large lists; and N is the number of elements in the specified range.

LREM.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the length of the list and M is the number of elements removed.

LSET.summary: Set the value of an element in a list by its index
LSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the list. Setting either the first or the last element of the list is O(1).

LTRIM.summary: Trim a list to the specified range
LTRIM.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to be removed by the operation.

MEMORY.summary: A container for memory diagnostics commands

MEMORY HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

MEMORY MALLOC-STATS.complexity: Depends on how much memory is allocated, could be slow

MEMORY PURGE.summary: Ask the allocator to release memory
MEMORY PURGE.complexity: Depends on how much memory is allocated, could be slow

MEMORY USAGE.summary: Estimate the memory usage of a key
MEMORY USAGE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of samples.

MGET.summary: Get the values of all the given keys
MGET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to retrieve.

MIGRATE.summary: Atomically transfer a key from a Redis instance to another one.
MIGRATE.complexity: This command actually executes a DUMP+DEL in the source instance, and a RESTORE in the target instance. See the pages of these commands for time complexity. Also an O(N) data transfer between the two instances is performed.

MODULE HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

MODULE LIST.summary: List all modules loaded by the server
MODULE LIST.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of loaded modules.

MODULE LOADEX.summary: Load a module with extended parameters

MONITOR.summary: Listen for all requests received by the server in real time

MOVE.summary: Move a key to another database

MSET.summary: Set multiple keys to multiple values
MSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

MSETNX.summary: Set multiple keys to multiple values, only if none of the keys exist
MSETNX.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

MULTI.summary: Mark the start of a transaction block

OBJECT.summary: A container for object introspection commands

OBJECT ENCODING.summary: Inspect the internal encoding of a Redis object

OBJECT FREQ.summary: Get the logarithmic access frequency counter of a Redis object

OBJECT HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

OBJECT IDLETIME.summary: Get the time since a Redis object was last accessed

OBJECT REFCOUNT.summary: Get the number of references to the value of the key

PERSIST.summary: Remove the expiration from a key

PEXPIRE.summary: Set a key's time to live in milliseconds

PEXPIREAT.summary: Set the expiration for a key as a UNIX timestamp specified in milliseconds

PEXPIRETIME.summary: Get the expiration Unix timestamp for a key in milliseconds

PFADD.summary: Adds the specified elements to the specified HyperLogLog.

PFCOUNT.summary: Return the approximated cardinality of the set(s) observed by the HyperLogLog at key(s).
PFCOUNT.complexity: O(1) with a very small average constant time when called with a single key. O(N) with N being the number of keys, and much bigger constant times, when called with multiple keys.

key_specs.notes: RW because it may change the internal representation of the key, and propagate to replicas

PFDEBUG.summary: Internal commands for debugging HyperLogLog values

PFMERGE.summary: Merge N different HyperLogLogs into a single one.
PFMERGE.complexity: O(N) to merge N HyperLogLogs, but with high constant times.

PFSELFTEST.summary: An internal command for testing HyperLogLog values

PSETEX.summary: Set the value and expiration in milliseconds of a key

PSUBSCRIBE.summary: Listen for messages published to channels matching the given patterns
PSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of patterns the client is already subscribed to.

PTTL.summary: Get the time to live for a key in milliseconds

PUBLISH.summary: Post a message to a channel
PUBLISH.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of clients subscribed to the receiving channel and M is the total number of subscribed patterns (by any client).

PUBSUB CHANNELS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of active channels, and assuming constant time pattern matching (relatively short channels and patterns)

PUBSUB HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

PUBSUB NUMPAT.summary: Get the count of unique patterns pattern subscriptions

PUBSUB NUMSUB.summary: Get the count of subscribers for channels
PUBSUB NUMSUB.complexity: O(N) for the NUMSUB subcommand, where N is the number of requested channels

PUBSUB SHARDCHANNELS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of active shard channels, and assuming constant time pattern matching (relatively short shard channels).

PUBSUB SHARDNUMSUB.summary: Get the count of subscribers for shard channels
PUBSUB SHARDNUMSUB.complexity: O(N) for the SHARDNUMSUB subcommand, where N is the number of requested shard channels

PUNSUBSCRIBE.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to channels matching the given patterns
PUNSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of patterns the client is already subscribed and M is the number of total patterns subscribed in the system (by any client).

RANDOMKEY.summary: Return a random key from the keyspace

READONLY.summary: Enables read queries for a connection to a cluster replica node

READWRITE.summary: Disables read queries for a connection to a cluster replica node

RENAMENX.summary: Rename a key, only if the new key does not exist
history: The command no longer returns an error when source and destination names are the same.

REPLCONF.summary: An internal command for configuring the replication stream

REPLICAOF.summary: Make the server a replica of another instance, or promote it as master.

RESTORE.summary: Create a key using the provided serialized value, previously obtained using DUMP.
RESTORE.complexity: O(1) to create the new key and additional O(N*M) to reconstruct the serialized value, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1). However for sorted set values the complexity is O(N*M*log(N)) because inserting values into sorted sets is O(log(N)).

RESTORE-ASKING.summary: An internal command for migrating keys in a cluster
RESTORE-ASKING.complexity: O(1) to create the new key and additional O(N*M) to reconstruct the serialized value, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1). However for sorted set values the complexity is O(N*M*log(N)) because inserting values into sorted sets is O(log(N)).

ROLE.summary: Return the role of the instance in the context of replication

RPOP.summary: Remove and get the last elements in a list
RPOP.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements returned

RPOPLPUSH.summary: Remove the last element in a list, prepend it to another list and return it

RPUSH.summary: Append one or multiple elements to a list
RPUSH.complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

RPUSHX.summary: Append an element to a list, only if the list exists
RPUSHX.complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

SADD.summary: Add one or more members to a set
SADD.complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

SAVE.summary: Synchronously save the dataset to disk
SAVE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of keys in all databases

SCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

SCARD.summary: Get the number of members in a set

SCRIPT.summary: A container for Lua scripts management commands

SCRIPT DEBUG.summary: Set the debug mode for executed scripts.

SCRIPT EXISTS.summary: Check existence of scripts in the script cache.
SCRIPT EXISTS.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts to check (so checking a single script is an O(1) operation).

SCRIPT FLUSH.summary: Remove all the scripts from the script cache.
SCRIPT FLUSH.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts in cache
history: Added the `ASYNC` and `SYNC` flushing mode modifiers.

SCRIPT HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

SCRIPT KILL.summary: Kill the script currently in execution.

SCRIPT LOAD.summary: Load the specified Lua script into the script cache.
SCRIPT LOAD.complexity: O(N) with N being the length in bytes of the script body.

SDIFF.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SDIFFSTORE.summary: Subtract multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SDIFFSTORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SELECT.summary: Change the selected database for the current connection

SET.summary: Set the string value of a key
history: Allowed the `NX` and `GET` options to be used together.

key_specs.notes: RW and ACCESS due to the optional `GET` argument

SETBIT.summary: Sets or clears the bit at offset in the string value stored at key

SETEX.summary: Set the value and expiration of a key

SETNX.summary: Set the value of a key, only if the key does not exist

SETRANGE.summary: Overwrite part of a string at key starting at the specified offset
SETRANGE.complexity: O(1), not counting the time taken to copy the new string in place. Usually, this string is very small so the amortized complexity is O(1). Otherwise, complexity is O(M) with M being the length of the value argument.

SHUTDOWN.summary: Synchronously save the dataset to disk and then shut down the server
SHUTDOWN.complexity: O(N) when saving, where N is the total number of keys in all databases when saving data, otherwise O(1)

SINTER.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

SINTERCARD.summary: Intersect multiple sets and return the cardinality of the result
SINTERCARD.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

SINTERSTORE.summary: Intersect multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SINTERSTORE.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

SISMEMBER.summary: Determine if a given value is a member of a set

SLAVEOF.summary: Make the server a replica of another instance, or promote it as master.

SLOWLOG.summary: A container for slow log commands

SLOWLOG GET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of entries returned
history: Added client IP address, port and name to the reply.

SLOWLOG HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

SLOWLOG RESET.summary: Clear all entries from the slow log
SLOWLOG RESET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of entries in the slowlog

SMEMBERS.summary: Get all the members in a set
SMEMBERS.complexity: O(N) where N is the set cardinality.

SMISMEMBER.summary: Returns the membership associated with the given elements for a set
SMISMEMBER.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements being checked for membership

SMOVE.summary: Move a member from one set to another

SORT.summary: Sort the elements in a list, set or sorted set
SORT.complexity: O(N+M*log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the list or set to sort, and M the number of returned elements. When the elements are not sorted, complexity is O(N).

key_specs.notes: For the optional BY/GET keyword. It is marked 'unknown' because the key names derive from the content of the key we sort
For the optional STORE keyword. It is marked 'unknown' because the keyword can appear anywhere in the argument array

SORT_RO.summary: Sort the elements in a list, set or sorted set. Read-only variant of SORT.
SORT_RO.complexity: O(N+M*log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the list or set to sort, and M the number of returned elements. When the elements are not sorted, complexity is O(N).

key_specs.notes: For the optional BY/GET keyword. It is marked 'unknown' because the key names derive from the content of the key we sort

SPOP.summary: Remove and return one or multiple random members from a set
SPOP.complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the value of the passed count.

SPUBLISH.summary: Post a message to a shard channel
SPUBLISH.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients subscribed to the receiving shard channel.

SRANDMEMBER.summary: Get one or multiple random members from a set
SRANDMEMBER.complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the absolute value of the passed count.

SREM.summary: Remove one or more members from a set
SREM.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members to be removed.

SSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..

SSUBSCRIBE.summary: Listen for messages published to the given shard channels
SSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of shard channels to subscribe to.

STRLEN.summary: Get the length of the value stored in a key

SUBSCRIBE.summary: Listen for messages published to the given channels
SUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of channels to subscribe to.

SUBSTR.summary: Get a substring of the string stored at a key
SUBSTR.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the returned string. The complexity is ultimately determined by the returned length, but because creating a substring from an existing string is very cheap, it can be considered O(1) for small strings.

SUNION.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SUNIONSTORE.summary: Add multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SUNIONSTORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SUNSUBSCRIBE.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to the given shard channels
SUNSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients already subscribed to a shard channel.

SWAPDB.complexity: O(N) where N is the count of clients watching or blocking on keys from both databases.

TOUCH.summary: Alters the last access time of a key(s). Returns the number of existing keys specified.
TOUCH.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys that will be touched.

TTL.summary: Get the time to live for a key in seconds

TYPE.summary: Determine the type stored at key

UNLINK.summary: Delete a key asynchronously in another thread. Otherwise it is just as DEL, but non blocking.
UNLINK.complexity: O(1) for each key removed regardless of its size. Then the command does O(N) work in a different thread in order to reclaim memory, where N is the number of allocations the deleted objects where composed of.

UNSUBSCRIBE.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to the given channels
UNSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients already subscribed to a channel.

WAIT.summary: Wait for the synchronous replication of all the write commands sent in the context of the current connection

WATCH.summary: Watch the given keys to determine execution of the MULTI/EXEC block

XACK.summary: Marks a pending message as correctly processed, effectively removing it from the pending entries list of the consumer group. Return value of the command is the number of messages successfully acknowledged, that is, the IDs we were actually able to resolve in the PEL.
XACK.complexity: O(1) for each message ID processed.

XADD.summary: Appends a new entry to a stream
XADD.complexity: O(1) when adding a new entry, O(N) when trimming where N being the number of entries evicted.
history: Added the `NOMKSTREAM` option, `MINID` trimming strategy and the `LIMIT` option.
Added support for the `<ms>-*` explicit ID form.

key_specs.notes: UPDATE instead of INSERT because of the optional trimming feature

XAUTOCLAIM.summary: Changes (or acquires) ownership of messages in a consumer group, as if the messages were delivered to the specified consumer.
history: Added an element to the reply array, containing deleted entries the command cleared from the PEL

XCLAIM.summary: Changes (or acquires) ownership of a message in a consumer group, as if the message was delivered to the specified consumer.
XCLAIM.complexity: O(log N) with N being the number of messages in the PEL of the consumer group.

XDEL.summary: Removes the specified entries from the stream. Returns the number of items actually deleted, that may be different from the number of IDs passed in case certain IDs do not exist.
XDEL.complexity: O(1) for each single item to delete in the stream, regardless of the stream size.

XGROUP.summary: A container for consumer groups commands

XGROUP CREATECONSUMER.summary: Create a consumer in a consumer group.

XGROUP DELCONSUMER.summary: Delete a consumer from a consumer group.

XGROUP DESTROY.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of entries in the group's pending entries list (PEL).

XGROUP HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

XGROUP SETID.summary: Set a consumer group to an arbitrary last delivered ID value.

XINFO.summary: A container for stream introspection commands

XINFO CONSUMERS.summary: List the consumers in a consumer group

XINFO GROUPS.summary: List the consumer groups of a stream

XINFO HELP.summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

XLEN.summary: Return the number of entries in a stream

XPENDING.summary: Return information and entries from a stream consumer group pending entries list, that are messages fetched but never acknowledged.
XPENDING.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements returned, so asking for a small fixed number of entries per call is O(1). O(M), where M is the total number of entries scanned when used with the IDLE filter. When the command returns just the summary and the list of consumers is small, it runs in O(1) time; otherwise, an additional O(N) time for iterating every consumer.
history: Added the `IDLE` option and exclusive range intervals.

XRANGE.summary: Return a range of elements in a stream, with IDs matching the specified IDs interval
XRANGE.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements being returned. If N is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1).

XREAD.summary: Return never seen elements in multiple streams, with IDs greater than the ones reported by the caller for each stream. Can block.
XREAD.complexity: For each stream mentioned: O(N) with N being the number of elements being returned, it means that XREAD-ing with a fixed COUNT is O(1). Note that when the BLOCK option is used, XADD will pay O(M) time in order to serve the M clients blocked on the stream getting new data.

XREADGROUP.summary: Return new entries from a stream using a consumer group, or access the history of the pending entries for a given consumer. Can block.
XREADGROUP.complexity: For each stream mentioned: O(M) with M being the number of elements returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1). On the other side when XREADGROUP blocks, XADD will pay the O(N) time in order to serve the N clients blocked on the stream getting new data.

XREVRANGE.summary: Return a range of elements in a stream, with IDs matching the specified IDs interval, in reverse order (from greater to smaller IDs) compared to XRANGE
XREVRANGE.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of elements returned. If N is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with COUNT), you can consider it O(1).

XSETID.summary: An internal command for replicating stream values

XTRIM.summary: Trims the stream to (approximately if '~' is passed) a certain size
XTRIM.complexity: O(N), with N being the number of evicted entries. Constant times are very small however, since entries are organized in macro nodes containing multiple entries that can be released with a single deallocation.
history: Added the `MINID` trimming strategy and the `LIMIT` option.

ZADD.summary: Add one or more members to a sorted set, or update its score if it already exists
ZADD.complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZCARD.summary: Get the number of members in a sorted set

ZCOUNT.summary: Count the members in a sorted set with scores within the given values
ZCOUNT.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZDIFF.complexity: O(L + (N-K)log(N)) worst case where L is the total number of elements in all the sets, N is the size of the first set, and K is the size of the result set.

ZDIFFSTORE.summary: Subtract multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key
ZDIFFSTORE.complexity: O(L + (N-K)log(N)) worst case where L is the total number of elements in all the sets, N is the size of the first set, and K is the size of the result set.

ZINCRBY.summary: Increment the score of a member in a sorted set
ZINCRBY.complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZINTER.complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

ZINTERCARD.summary: Intersect multiple sorted sets and return the cardinality of the result
ZINTERCARD.complexity: O(N*K) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets.

ZINTERSTORE.summary: Intersect multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key
ZINTERSTORE.complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

ZLEXCOUNT.summary: Count the number of members in a sorted set between a given lexicographical range
ZLEXCOUNT.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZMPOP.summary: Remove and return members with scores in a sorted set
ZMPOP.complexity: O(K) + O(N*log(M)) where K is the number of provided keys, N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

ZMSCORE.summary: Get the score associated with the given members in a sorted set
ZMSCORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members being requested.

ZPOPMAX.summary: Remove and return members with the highest scores in a sorted set
ZPOPMAX.complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

ZPOPMIN.summary: Remove and return members with the lowest scores in a sorted set
ZPOPMIN.complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

ZRANDMEMBER.summary: Get one or multiple random elements from a sorted set
ZRANDMEMBER.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements returned

ZRANGE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set
ZRANGE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

ZRANGEBYLEX.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range
ZRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score
ZRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZRANGESTORE.summary: Store a range of members from sorted set into another key
ZRANGESTORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements stored into the destination key.

ZRANK.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set

ZREM.summary: Remove one or more members from a sorted set
ZREM.complexity: O(M*log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements to be removed.

ZREMRANGEBYLEX.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set between the given lexicographical range
ZREMRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREMRANGEBYRANK.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given indexes
ZREMRANGEBYRANK.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREMRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given scores
ZREMRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREVRANGE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by index, with scores ordered from high to low
ZREVRANGE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

ZREVRANGEBYLEX.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range, ordered from higher to lower strings.
ZREVRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZREVRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score, with scores ordered from high to low
ZREVRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZREVRANK.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set, with scores ordered from high to low

ZSCAN.summary: Incrementally iterate sorted sets elements and associated scores
ZSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..

ZSCORE.summary: Get the score associated with the given member in a sorted set

ZUNION.complexity: O(N)+O(M*log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

ZUNIONSTORE.summary: Add multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key
ZUNIONSTORE.complexity: O(N)+O(M log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

FT.CREATE.summary: Creates an index with the given spec
FT.CREATE.complexity: O(K) at creation where K is the number of fields, O(N) if scanning the keyspace is triggered, where N is the number of keys in the keyspace
history: Added `PAYLOAD_FIELD` argument for backward support of `FT.SEARCH` deprecated `WITHPAYLOADS` argument

FT.INFO.summary: Returns information and statistics on the index

FT.EXPLAIN.summary: Returns the execution plan for a complex query

FT.EXPLAINCLI.summary: Returns the execution plan for a complex query

FT.ALTER.summary: Adds a new field to the index
FT.ALTER.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys in the keyspace

FT.DROPINDEX.complexity: O(1) or O(N) if documents are deleted, where N is the number of keys in the keyspace

FT.ALIASADD.summary: Adds an alias to the index

FT.ALIASUPDATE.summary: Adds or updates an alias to the index

FT.ALIASDEL.summary: Deletes an alias from the index

FT.TAGVALS.summary: Returns the distinct tags indexed in a Tag field

FT.SUGADD.summary: Adds a suggestion string to an auto-complete suggestion dictionary

FT.SUGGET.summary: Gets completion suggestions for a prefix

FT.SUGDEL.summary: Deletes a string from a suggestion index

FT.SUGLEN.summary: Gets the size of an auto-complete suggestion dictionary

FT.SYNUPDATE.summary: Creates or updates a synonym group with additional terms

FT.SYNDUMP.summary: Dumps the contents of a synonym group

FT.SPELLCHECK.summary: Performs spelling correction on a query, returning suggestions for misspelled terms

FT.DICTDUMP.summary: Dumps all terms in the given dictionary
FT.DICTDUMP.complexity: O(N), where N is the size of the dictionary

FT._LIST.summary: Returns a list of all existing indexes

FT.CONFIG HELP.summary: Help description of runtime configuration options

FT.SEARCH.summary: Searches the index with a textual query, returning either documents or just ids

FT.PROFILE.summary: Performs a `FT.SEARCH` or `FT.AGGREGATE` command and collects performance information

JSON.DEL.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the deleted value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.FORGET.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the deleted value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.GET.summary: Gets the value at one or more paths in JSON serialized form
JSON.GET.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.TOGGLE.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.CLEAR.summary: Clears all values from an array or an object and sets numeric values to `0`
JSON.CLEAR.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the values, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.SET.summary: Sets or updates the JSON value at a path
JSON.SET.complexity: O(M+N) when path is evaluated to a single value where M is the size of the original value (if it exists) and N is the size of the new value, O(M+N) when path is evaluated to multiple values where M is the size of the key and N is the size of the new value

JSON.MGET.summary: Returns the values at a path from one or more keys
JSON.MGET.complexity: O(M*N) when path is evaluated to a single value where M is the number of keys and N is the size of the value, O(N1+N2+...+Nm) when path is evaluated to multiple values where m is the number of keys and Ni is the size of the i-th key

JSON.NUMINCRBY.summary: Increments the numeric value at path by a value
JSON.NUMINCRBY.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.NUMMULTBY.summary: Multiplies the numeric value at path by a value
JSON.NUMMULTBY.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.STRAPPEND.summary: Appends a string to a JSON string value at path
JSON.STRAPPEND.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.STRLEN.summary: Returns the length of the JSON String at path in key
JSON.STRLEN.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRAPPEND.summary: Append one or more json values into the array at path after the last element in it.
JSON.ARRAPPEND.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRINDEX.summary: Returns the index of the first occurrence of a JSON scalar value in the array at path
JSON.ARRINDEX.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the array, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRINSERT.summary: Inserts the JSON scalar(s) value at the specified index in the array at path
JSON.ARRINSERT.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the array, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRLEN.summary: Returns the length of the array at path
JSON.ARRLEN.complexity: O(1) where path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) where path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRPOP.summary: Removes and returns the element at the specified index in the array at path
JSON.ARRPOP.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the array and the specified index is not the last element, O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value and the specified index is the last element, or O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.ARRTRIM.summary: Trims the array at path to contain only the specified inclusive range of indices from start to stop
JSON.ARRTRIM.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value where N is the size of the array, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.OBJKEYS.summary: Returns the JSON keys of the object at path
JSON.OBJKEYS.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value, where N is the number of keys in the object, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.OBJLEN.summary: Returns the number of keys of the object at path
JSON.OBJLEN.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.TYPE.summary: Returns the type of the JSON value at path
JSON.TYPE.complexity: O(1) when path is evaluated to a single value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.RESP.summary: Returns the JSON value at path in Redis Serialization Protocol (RESP)
JSON.RESP.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value, where N is the size of the value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

JSON.DEBUG MEMORY.summary: Reports the size in bytes of a key
JSON.DEBUG MEMORY.complexity: O(N) when path is evaluated to a single value, where N is the size of the value, O(N) when path is evaluated to multiple values, where N is the size of the key

GRAPH.QUERY.summary: Executes the given query against a specified graph

GRAPH.RO_QUERY.summary: Executes a given read only query against a specified graph

GRAPH.DELETE.summary: Completely removes the graph and all of its entities

GRAPH.EXPLAIN.summary: Returns a query execution plan without running the query

GRAPH.PROFILE.summary: Executes a query and returns an execution plan augmented with metrics for each operation's execution

GRAPH.SLOWLOG.summary: Returns a list containing up to 10 of the slowest queries issued against the given graph

GRAPH.LIST.summary: Lists all graph keys in the keyspace

TS.DEL.summary: Delete all samples between two timestamps for a given time series
TS.DEL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of data points that will be removed

TS.ALTER.summary: Update the retention, chunk size, duplicate policy, and labels of an existing time series
TS.ALTER.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of labels requested to update

TS.ADD.summary: Append a sample to a time series
TS.ADD.complexity: O(M) when M is the amount of compaction rules or O(1) with no compaction

TS.MADD.summary: Append new samples to one or more time series
TS.MADD.complexity: O(N*M) when N is the amount of series updated and M is the amount of compaction rules or O(N) with no compaction

TS.INCRBY.summary: Increase the value of the sample with the maximal existing timestamp, or create a new sample with a value equal to the value of the sample with the maximal existing timestamp with a given increment
TS.INCRBY.complexity: O(M) when M is the amount of compaction rules or O(1) with no compaction

TS.DECRBY.summary: Decrease the value of the sample with the maximal existing timestamp, or create a new sample with a value equal to the value of the sample with the maximal existing timestamp with a given decrement
TS.DECRBY.complexity: O(M) when M is the amount of compaction rules or O(1) with no compaction

TS.RANGE.summary: Query a range in forward direction
TS.RANGE.complexity: O(n/m+k) where n = Number of data points, m = Chunk size (data points per chunk), k = Number of data points that are in the requested range

TS.REVRANGE.summary: Query a range in reverse direction
TS.REVRANGE.complexity: O(n/m+k) where n = Number of data points, m = Chunk size (data points per chunk), k = Number of data points that are in the requested range

TS.MRANGE.summary: Query a range across multiple time series by filters in forward direction
TS.MRANGE.complexity: O(n/m+k) where n = Number of data points, m = Chunk size (data points per chunk), k = Number of data points that are in the requested ranges

TS.MREVRANGE.summary: Query a range across multiple time-series by filters in reverse direction
TS.MREVRANGE.complexity: O(n/m+k) where n = Number of data points, m = Chunk size (data points per chunk), k = Number of data points that are in the requested ranges

TS.MGET.summary: Get the last samples matching a specific filter
TS.MGET.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of time-series that match the filters

TS.INFO.summary: Returns information and statistics for a time series

TS.QUERYINDEX.summary: Get all time series keys matching a filter list
TS.QUERYINDEX.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of time-series that match the filters

BF.ADD.summary: Adds an item to a Bloom Filter
BF.ADD.complexity: O(k), where k is the number of hash functions used by the last sub-filter

BF.MADD.summary: Adds one or more items to a Bloom Filter. A filter will be created if it does not exist
BF.MADD.complexity: O(k * n), where k is the number of hash functions and n is the number of items

BF.INSERT.summary: Adds one or more items to a Bloom Filter. A filter will be created if it does not exist
BF.INSERT.complexity: O(k * n), where k is the number of hash functions and n is the number of items

BF.EXISTS.summary: Checks whether an item exists in a Bloom Filter
BF.EXISTS.complexity: O(k), where k is the number of hash functions used by the last sub-filter

BF.MEXISTS.summary: Checks whether one or more items exist in a Bloom Filter
BF.MEXISTS.complexity: O(k * n), where k is the number of hash functions and n is the number of items

BF.SCANDUMP.summary: Begins an incremental save of the bloom filter
BF.SCANDUMP.complexity: O(n), where n is the capacity

BF.LOADCHUNK.summary: Restores a filter previously saved using SCANDUMP
BF.LOADCHUNK.complexity: O(n), where n is the capacity

BF.INFO.summary: Returns information about a Bloom Filter

CF.ADD.summary: Adds an item to a Cuckoo Filter
CF.ADD.complexity: O(k + i), where k is the number of sub-filters and i is maxIterations

CF.ADDNX.summary: Adds an item to a Cuckoo Filter if the item did not exist previously.
CF.ADDNX.complexity: O(k + i), where k is the number of sub-filters and i is maxIterations

CF.INSERT.summary: Adds one or more items to a Cuckoo Filter. A filter will be created if it does not exist
CF.INSERT.complexity: O(n * (k + i)), where n is the number of items, k is the number of sub-filters and i is maxIterations

CF.INSERTNX.summary: Adds one or more items to a Cuckoo Filter if the items did not exist previously. A filter will be created if it does not exist
CF.INSERTNX.complexity: O(n * (k + i)), where n is the number of items, k is the number of sub-filters and i is maxIterations

CF.EXISTS.summary: Checks whether one or more items exist in a Cuckoo Filter
CF.EXISTS.complexity: O(k), where k is the number of sub-filters

CF.MEXISTS.summary: Checks whether one or more items exist in a Cuckoo Filter
CF.MEXISTS.complexity: O(k * n), where k is the number of sub-filters and n is the number of items

CF.DEL.summary: Deletes an item from a Cuckoo Filter
CF.DEL.complexity: O(k), where k is the number of sub-filters

CF.COUNT.summary: Return the number of times an item might be in a Cuckoo Filter
CF.COUNT.complexity: O(k), where k is the number of sub-filters

CF.SCANDUMP.summary: Begins an incremental save of the bloom filter
CF.SCANDUMP.complexity: O(n), where n is the capacity

CF.LOADCHUNK.summary: Restores a filter previously saved using SCANDUMP
CF.LOADCHUNK.complexity: O(n), where n is the capacity

CF.INFO.summary: Returns information about a Cuckoo Filter

CMS.INITBYDIM.summary: Initializes a Count-Min Sketch to dimensions specified by user

CMS.INITBYPROB.summary: Initializes a Count-Min Sketch to accommodate requested tolerances.

CMS.INCRBY.summary: Increases the count of one or more items by increment
CMS.INCRBY.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of items

CMS.QUERY.summary: Returns the count for one or more items in a sketch
CMS.QUERY.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of items

CMS.MERGE.summary: Merges several sketches into one sketch
CMS.MERGE.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of sketches

TOPK.RESERVE.summary: Initializes a TopK with specified parameters

TOPK.ADD.summary: Increases the count of one or more items by increment
TOPK.ADD.complexity: O(n * k) where n is the number of items and k is the depth

TOPK.INCRBY.summary: Increases the count of one or more items by increment
TOPK.INCRBY.complexity: O(n * k * incr) where n is the number of items, k is the depth and incr is the increment

TOPK.QUERY.summary: Checks whether one or more items are in a sketch
TOPK.QUERY.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of items

TOPK.Count.summary: Return the count for one or more items are in a sketch
TOPK.Count.complexity: O(n) where n is the number of items

TOPK.LIST.summary: Return full list of items in Top K list
TOPK.LIST.complexity: O(k) where k is the value of top-k

TDIGEST.CREATE.summary: Allocate the memory and initialize the t-digest

TDIGEST.RESET.summary: Reset the sketch to zero - empty out the sketch and re-initialize it

TDIGEST.ADD.summary: Adds one or more samples to a sketch
TDIGEST.ADD.complexity: O(N) , where N is the number of samples to add

TDIGEST.MERGE.summary: Merges all of the values from 'from' to 'this' sketch
TDIGEST.MERGE.complexity: O(N), where N is the number of centroids

TDIGEST.MIN.summary: Get minimum value from the sketch

TDIGEST.MAX.summary: Get maximum value from the sketch

TDIGEST.QUANTILE.summary: Returns an estimate of the cutoff such that a specified fraction of the data added to this TDigest would be less than or equal to the specified cutoffs. Multiple quantiles can be returned with one call.

TDIGEST.CDF.summary: Returns the fraction of all points added which are <= value

TDIGEST.TRIMMED_MEAN.summary: Returns the trimmed mean ignoring values outside given cutoff upper and lower limits
